'''One Direction''' (commonly initialised as '''1D''') are an English-Irish<!-- Please do not change English-Irish to anything else without first discussing it in this article's talk page --> [[pop music|pop]] [[boy band]] based in London, consisting of [[Niall Horan]], [[Zayn Malik]], [[Liam Payne]], [[Harry Styles]] and [[Louis Tomlinson]]. They signed with [[Simon Cowell]]'s record label [[Syco Music|Syco Records]] after being formed and finishing third in the [[The X Factor (UK series 7)|seventh series]] of the British televised singing competition ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]'' in 2010. Propelled to international success by the power of [[social media]], One Direction's three albums, ''[[Up All Night (One Direction album)|Up All Night]]'', ''[[Take Me Home (One Direction album)|Take Me Home]]'' and ''[[Midnight Memories]]'', (released in 2011, 2012 and 2013 respectively), broke several records, topped the charts of most major markets, and generated hit singles, which include "[[What Makes You Beautiful]]", "[[Live While We're Young]]" and "[[Story of My Life (One Direction song)|Story of My Life]]".

[[List of awards and nominations received by One Direction|Their achievements]] include four [[Brit Awards]] and four [[MTV Video Music Awards]] among many others. According to Nick Gatfield, the chairman and chief executive of [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music Entertainment UK]], One Direction represented a $50 million business empire by June 2012. They were proclaimed 2012's "Top New Artist" by [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1481395/one-direction-qas-with-billboards-top-new-artist-of-2012 |title=One Direction: Q&As With Billboard's Top New Artist of 2012 | first =Andrew | last = Hampp |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher= [[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=14 December 2012 |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref> According to the ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'', by April 2013 they had an estimated personal combined wealth of <U+00A3>25&nbsp;million ($41.2m) making them the second wealthiest musicians in the UK under 30 years of age.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.sugarscape.com/main-topics/celebrities/851889/sunday-times-rich-list-2013-one-direction-zoom-under-30s-paul-mccartn|work=[[sugarscape.com]]|title=Sunday Times<U+2019> rich list 2013, One direction, Zoom under 30, Paul McCartney}}</ref> After the release of ''Midnight Memories'', One Direction became the first band in US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] history to have their first three albums debut at number one.<ref name="Billboard record"/> Additionally, the album was a global success, debuting at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and becoming the fastest and biggest selling album of 2013 in the UK.

==History==

===2010<U+2013>11: ''The X Factor''===
[[File:One Direction X Factor Live Glasgow.jpg|thumb|left|One Direction on ''The X Factor'' Live tour in 2011]]
In 2010, [[Niall Horan]], [[Zayn Malik]], [[Liam Payne]], [[Harry Styles]], and [[Louis Tomlinson]] auditioned as solo candidates for the [[The X Factor (UK series 7)|seventh series]] of the British televised singing competition ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]''.<ref name=Kelly>{{cite news| first =Kristy | last = Kelly | url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a331792/nicole-scherzinger-i-did-simon-cowell-a-favour-with-one-direction.html | title= Nicole Scherzinger: 'I did Simon Cowell a favour with One Direction' |work= [[Digital Spy]]| publisher= Hearst | place = UK|date= 26 July 2011 | accessdate =26 July 2011}}</ref> They failed to progress to the "Boys" category at "[[The X Factor (UK series 7)#Judges' houses and wildcards|judges' houses]]" but were put together to form a five-piece boy band at [[Wembley Arena]], in London, England, in July 2010, during the "[[The X Factor (UK series 7)#Bootcamp|bootcamp]]" stage of the competition,<ref>{{cite news| first = Kate | last = McMahon| url = http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/07/12/cheryl-tweedy-cancels-x-factor-boot-camp-and-v-festival-appearances-115875-22406276/ | title= Cheryl Tweedy cancels X Factor Boot Camp and V Festival appearances | work = The Daily Mirror |publisher= [[Trinity Mirror]]|date= 12 July 2010|accessdate= 12 July 2010}}</ref> thus qualifying for the "Groups" category. [[Nicole Scherzinger]], a guest judge,<ref name=Kelly /><ref>{{cite news|title=One Direction film claims she founded band, not Simon Cowell|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/07/19/more-woe-for-nicole-scherzinger-one-direction-film-claims-she-founded-band-not-simon-cowell/|newspaper=[[The Independent]] | location=London|first=Daisy|last=Wyatt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Without Nicole Scherzinger there would be no One Direction|url=http://www.novafm.com.au/audio/without-nicole-scherzinger-there-would-be-no-one-direction|newspaper=NOVA Fm (Australian radio)}}</ref> and Simon Cowell have both claimed to have come up with the idea of forming the band. In 2013, Cowell said that it "took him 10 minutes to put them together as a group".<ref name="1D Day">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a533467/simon-cowell-talks-one-direction-formation-it-was-my-idea.html|title=Simon Cowell talks One Direction formation: 'It was my idea'|last=Harp|first=Justin|date=24 November 2013|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> Subsequently, the group got together for two weeks to get to know each other and to practise.<ref name = "thehothits1">{{cite news| first1 =Stan | last1 = Walker | first2 = Short | last2 = Stack | first3 = Michael | last3 = Paynter | first4 = Amy | last4 = Meredith |url= http://www.thehothits.com/artists/6069/one-direction/bio |title= One Direction Biography | work= [[The Hot Hits Live from LA]]| publisher= MCM Media | accessdate= 27 April 2012}}</ref><ref name = autogenerated10>{{cite web| newspaper =South Wales Echo |url= http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2012/01/13/one-direction-prepare-for-cardiff-sell-out-shows-91466-30112196/ |title= One Direction prepare for Cardiff sell-out shows|publisher=[[Media Wales]] |date=13 January 2012 | accessdate =6 June 2012}}</ref> Styles came up with the name One Direction.<ref name="thehothits1" /> For their qualifying song at "judges' houses", and their first song as a group, One Direction sang an acoustic version of "[[Torn (Ednaswap song)|Torn]]".<ref>{{cite web|url = http://entertainment.stv.tv/tv/200816-the-x-factor-2010-the-acts-who-made-it-to-the-live-shows/ | work = [[STV (TV network)|STV]] |place =[[Scotland|SCO]], UK |title= The X Factor 2010: the 12 acts who made it to the Live Shows |date=3 October 2010|accessdate= 4 November 2011}}</ref> Cowell later commented that their performance convinced him that they "were confident, fun, like a gang of friends, and kind of fearless as well."<ref name = "simoncowellQ&A">{{cite news| first = Andy | last = Greene |url = http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/exclusive-q-a-simon-cowell-on-one-directions-rise-to-stardom-20120409 |title=Exclusive Q&A: Simon Cowell on One Direction's Rise to Stardom |work=Rolling Stone |publisher=[[Jann Wenner]] |date= 9 April 2012 |accessdate= 11 May 2012}}</ref> Within the first four weeks of the [[The X Factor (UK series 7)#Live show details|live shows]], they were his last act in the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1325412/X-Factor-2010-Belle-Amie-voted-Katie-Waissel-survives-week.html |title=X Factor 2010: Flaky Katie Waissel survives by the skin of her teeth as Simon Cowell is down to one act after Belle Amie are voted off| last= Bull|first= Sarah|date= 31 October 2010|work= The Daily Mail | publisher =[[Associated Newspapers]]|accessdate=26 August 2012|location=London}}</ref> The group quickly gained popularity in the UK.<ref name="simoncowellQ&A" />

One Direction finished in third place and immediately after the final, their song "[[Forever Young (Alphaville song)|Forever Young]]", which would have been released if they had won ''The X Factor'', was leaked onto the internet.<ref name = thirdplace>{{cite news|url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/dec/10/xfactor-final-results-liveblog |title=The X Factor 2010 final results show|work=The Guardian|date= 12 December 2012 |accessdate=15 March 2012 | location = London | first = Stuart | last = Heritage}}</ref> Shortly afterwards it was confirmed that One Direction had been signed by Cowell to a reported [[Pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]2 million [[Syco Music|Syco Records]] record contract.<ref>{{cite news | first = Lee | last = Cara | url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/x_factor/3277896/Simon-Cowell-snaps-up-Cher-Rebecca-and-One-Direction.html |title=Father Xmas Si's three special gifts |work= The Sun | publisher = [[News International]] |date= 15 December 2010 |accessdate= 4 January 2012 |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Mayer | last = Nissim |url= http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/s103/the-x-factor/news/a300729/one-direction-get-gbp2m-syco-investment.html | title= One Direction 'get <U+00A3>2m Syco investment' | work= [[Digital Spy]] | publisher = Hearst | place = UK | date=28 January 2011|accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> Recording for their debut album began in January 2011, as they flew to Los Angeles to work with [[RedOne]], a record producer.<ref name = Miller>{{cite news | first = Ed | last = Miller |url = http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/sony-excited-about-one-direction-potential/046464 | title = Sony excited about One Direction potential |work= [[Music Week]] |publisher= Intent Media |date = 16 August 2011 | accessdate = 27 July 2012}}</ref> A book licensed by One Direction, ''One Direction: Forever Young (Our Official X Factor Story)'', was published by [[HarperCollins]] in February 2011,<ref>{{cite web| first =Alex  | last = Fletcher | url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/s103/the-x-factor/news/a304324/one-direction-release-autobiography.html | title= One Direction release autobiography |work= [[Digital Spy]]|publisher= Hearst | place = UK | date = 17 February 2011 | accessdate=14 January 2012}}</ref> subsequently topping [[The Sunday Times|''The Sunday Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.sugarscape.com/tags/band/621789/one-direction-number-one-sunday-times-bestseller-list?page=0%2C0 |title=One Direction book number one on Sunday Times bestsetller list |work= [[Sugar (magazine)|Sugarscape]] |publisher= [[Hachette Filipacchi M<U+00E9>dias]] |date= 5 April 2011|accessdate= 27 July 2012}}</ref> The same month, the boy band and other contestants from the series participated in the ''X Factor'' Live Tour.<ref>{{cite news | first =Sophie | last = Freeman |title= Now Treyc Cohen snubbed by X Factor for <U+00A3>100,000 tour... but reject Aiden Grimshaw IS invited |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1331129/X-Factor-2010-Treyc-Cohen-snubbed-Aiden-Grimshaw-stays-tour.html | work= The Daily Mail | publisher= [[Associated Newspapers]] | date= 19 November 2010 | accessdate = 19 November 2010 |location= London}}</ref> During the tour the group performed for 500,000 people throughout the UK.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.hmvtickets.com/events/1622?REFID=hmv_tickets_system_body |title=Tickets for One Direction at HMV Apollo Hammersmith, London, now available from hmvtickets.com |publisher= [[HMV]] |accessdate= 11 May 2012}}</ref>  After the tour concluded in April 2011, the group continued working on their debut album.<ref name = Miller /> Recording took place in Stockholm, London and [[Los Angeles]], as One Direction worked with producers [[Carl Falk]], [[Savan Kotecha]], [[Steve Mac]], and [[Rami (producer)|Rami Yacoub]], among others.<ref name="allmusic1">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-all-night-r2324993/credits |title= Up All Night <U+2013> One Direction |publisher = AllMusic | publisher =[[Rovi Corporation]] |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media notes | title =Up All Night |others=One Direction |date=2011 |type=liner notes |publisher= [[Syco Music]], [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref>

===2011<U+2013>12: ''Up All Night''===
Released in September 2011, One Direction's debut single, "[[What Makes You Beautiful]]", reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]], after becoming the most pre-ordered [[Sony Music Entertainment]] single in history.<ref>{{cite news | first =Lewis | last = Corner |url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a335956/one-directions-what-makes-you-beautiful-breaks-pre-order-sales-record.html | title=One Direction's 'What Makes You Beautiful' breaks pre-order sales record |work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Hearst | place = UK|date=19 August 2011|accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Alan | last = Jones | url = http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=22&storycode=1046622 | title = What Makes You Beautiful becomes fastest seller of the year | work= [[Music Week]] | publisher = Intent Media |date = 19 September 2011 |accessdate= 5 January 2012}}</ref> Subsequent singles, "[[Gotta Be You (One Direction song)|Gotta Be You]]" and "[[One Thing (One Direction song)|One Thing]]", peaked in the UK Singles Chart top ten.<ref>{{cite news| first = Alan | last = Jones |url= http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1047553&c=1 |title=UK Singles Chart Analysis: Rihanna equals Adele record |work=[[Music Week]] |publisher = Intent Media|date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first =Alan | last = Jones |url = http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1048551&c=1 |title = Official Chart Analysis: Emeli Sande album sells 113k, DJ Fresh single shifts 128k |work= [[Music Week]] |publisher=Intent Media |date=20 February 2012 | accessdate = 17 March 2012}}</ref>  In November 2011, they signed a record deal with [[Columbia Records]] in North America.<ref>{{cite web| first = Lewis | last = Corner| url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a352201/one-direction-sign-us-record-deal-with-adele-label-columbia.html |title=One Direction sign US record deal with Adele label Columbia | work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher= Hearst | place = UK |date= 22 November 2011 |accessdate= 14 January 2012}}</ref> [[Steve Barnett (music executive)|Steve Barnett]], the co-chairman of Columbia Records, said it was not a difficult decision to sign One Direction; "I just thought there was a void, and maybe they could seize and hold it."<ref>{{cite news| first =James C, Jr | last = McKinley | url= http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/24/arts/music/one-direction-and-the-wanted-boy-bands-return.html |work= [[The New York Times]] | title= One Direction and the Wanted: Boy Bands Return | date=23 March 2012}}</ref> "What Makes You Beautiful" was released in the United States in February 2012,<ref>{{cite news| first =Amanda | last = Hasaka |url= http://www.celebuzz.com/2012-02-14/one-directions-debut-single-what-makes-you-beautiful-now-available-on-itunes/ |title=One Direction's Debut Single 'What Makes You Beautiful' Now Available On iTunes! |work= Celebuzz |publisher=[[Buzz Media]]|date=14 February 2012 |accessdate= 15 February 2012}}</ref> where it debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 28, becoming the highest debut for a British act since 1998.<ref name="Hot100">{{cite web |url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/504475/one-direction-has-highest-hot-100-debut-for-new-uk-act-since-1998 |title= One Direction Has Highest Hot 100 Debut For New UK Act Since 1998 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher= [[Prometheus Global Media]] |date= 22 February 2012 |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> It has sold over 4 million copies in the US.<ref name="sales2013">{{cite news |url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-jan-27-2013-songs-another-f-233455441.html |title= Week Ending Jan. 27, 2013. Songs: Another F**kin<U+2019> Top 10 Hit | first =Paul | last = Grein|work=[[Yahoo! Music|Music]] | publisher = [[Yahoo!]] |date=30 January 2013 |accessdate= 30 January 2013}}</ref> Upon arrival in the US in February 2012, One Direction embarked on a radio promotion spree, as well as their first North American concert tour as an opening act for [[Big Time Rush (band)|Big Time Rush]].<ref>{{cite news| first =Mark | last = Savage|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18083174 |title= The US love affair with British pop|work= News |publisher= BBC|date= 21 May 2010 | accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| first =Stephan | last = Lee|url= http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/02/03/one-direction-big-time-rush-exclusive-photo/ | title= Exclusive Photo: One Direction and Big Time Rush unite for North American tour!|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]] |accessdate= 4 February 2012}}</ref> They made their first US television appearance on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'', at the [[Rockefeller Center]]; an estimated 15,000 fans descended on the plaza.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/499360/one-direction-the-wanted-the-billboard-cover-story |title=One Direction & The Wanted: The Billboard Cover Story | first =Steven J | last = Horowitz |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher= [[Prometheus Global Media]] |date= 27 March 2012 | accessdate =16 April 2012}}</ref> Critically commended for its appeal to the teenage audience,<ref>{{cite news| first = Adam | last = Markovitz | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20578458,00.html | type = review | title = Up All Night (2012) One Direction |work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time |date= 20 March 2012| accessdate =21 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/story/2012-03-12/one-direction-up-all-night/53502638/1 | title = Listen Up: Stay 'Up All Night' with One Direction|work= USA Today | publisher = [[Gannett Company|Gannett Co]] | date= 13 March 2012 | accessdate= 31 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Matthew | last = Chisling | url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-all-night-r2324993/review |title=Up All Night&nbsp;<U+2013> One Direction| work = AllMusic | publisher =[[Rovi Corporation]] |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate= 5 January 2012}}</ref> One Direction's first studio album, ''[[Up All Night (One Direction album)|Up All Night]]'', was released globally in early 2012. It became the UK's fastest-selling debut album of 2011,<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/thank-fans-up-all-night-chart-success/ |title= One Direction Thank Fans For 'Up All Night' Chart Success |work= [[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|publisher=[[Global Radio]]|date= 28 November 2011 |accessdate=14 January 2012}}</ref> and topped the charts in sixteen countries.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/one-direction-to-hold-global-twitter-viewing-party-for-new-concert-dvd/049052 | title = One Direction to hold global Twitter viewing party for new concert DVD | work= [[Music Week]] | publisher = Intent Media | date=30 May 2012 |accessdate= 11 June 2012}}</ref> The album bowed atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, making One Direction the first British group in US chart history to enter at number one with their debut album.<ref>{{cite news| first =Keith | last = Caulfield | title = One Direction Makes History With No.&nbsp;1 Debut on Billboard 200|url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/499420/one-direction-makes-history-with-no-1-debut-on-billboard-200 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher = [[Prometheus Global Media]] | date = 20 March 2012 | accessdate= 21 March 2012}}</ref> They were inducted into the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as a result.<ref>{{cite news| first = Colin | last = Daniels| url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a404538/adele-one-direction-enter-guinness-world-records.html |title=Adele, One Direction enter 'Guinness World Records' | work = [[Digital Spy]] |publisher=Hearst | place = UK |date=7 September 2012 | accessdate =8 September 2012}}</ref> ''Up All Night'' also became the first album by a boy band to sell 500,000 digital copies in the US and, by August 2012, had sold over 3 million copies worldwide.<ref name = "Yahoosales">{{cite news | title = Week Ending Oct. 21, 2012. Albums: Aldean<U+2019>s Fast Train To #1 | url = http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-oct-21-2012-albums-aldean-fast-150305200.html | first =Paul | last = Grein |work= Music |publisher = Yahoo! |date= 24 October 2012 | accessdate = 24 October 2012|location= [[United States of America|US]]}}</ref><ref name = "12millionsales">{{cite web| first =Dan | last = Lane|url = http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-sell-12-million-singles-albums-and-dvd-and-blu-rays-worldwide-1516/ |title = One Direction sell 12 million singles, albums and DVD and Blu-rays worldwide | publisher = [[Official Charts Company]] |date=2 August 2012 |accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref>

[[File:One Direction Sydney 6.jpg|thumb|right|One Direction performing on their [[Up All Night Tour]], April 2012]]
In April 2012, an American band that went by the same name filed a [[trademark infringement]] lawsuit.<ref name = trademark>{{cite news| first =Rhian | last = Jones |url= http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/one-direction-sued-for-trademark-infringement/048557 |title=One Direction sued for trademark infringement |work= [[Music Week]] |publisher = Intent Media | date= 11 April 2012 |accessdate= 27 April 2012}}</ref> According to the lawsuit, the US band had been using the name since 2009, recorded two albums and filed an application to register the trademark name in the US in February 2011.<ref name=trademark/> The US band said they were entitled to three times the profits made by the UK band, as well as compensatory damages in excess of US$1million.<ref name=trademark/> The lawsuit claimed that Syco and Sony Music "chose to ignore the plaintiff's rights and wilfully infringed them" after they realised in early 2011 that the two bands shared the same name.<ref name=trademark/> Syco Records subsequently counter-sued, suggesting the US group was trying to make money from One Direction's success and that the boy band was the first to use the name in US interstate commerce.<ref name=lawsuit/> The [[BBC]] reported in September 2012 that the UK group won the legal dispute over the right to keep using their band name; the US band changed its name to Uncharted Shores.<ref name=lawsuit/> The change of name was announced in a joint statement that also noted both groups were happy with the outcome.<ref name = lawsuit>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/19473197 |title= One Direction win fight against US band to keep name | work =[[Newsbeat]] |publisher=BBC |date=7 September 2012|accessdate=8 September 2012}}</ref>

In December 2011, One Direction embarked on their first headlining UK concert tour, the [[Up All Night Tour]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/up-all-night-tour-watford/ |title= One Direction Prepare For 'Up All Night' Tour With Watford Concert |work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|publisher=[[Global Radio]] | date =19 December 2011| accessdate= 27 March 2012|archiveurl= http://www.freezepage.com/1333935031UMDTEVHWRV | archivedate = 8 April 2012}}</ref> In early 2012, they announced Australasian and North American legs of the concert tour, with dates from April to July 2012.<ref>{{cite news| first =Lisa | last = McGarry |url = http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/x-factor/one-direction-announce-tour-dates-for-australia-and-new-zealand/ |title= One Direction announce 2012 tour dates for Australia and New Zealand |work= Unreality TV | date= 24 February 2012 | accessdate = 31 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://idolator.com/6226892/one-direction-north-american-tour-dates |title=One Direction Reveal North American Tour Dates |work= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |publisher= [[Buzz Media]]|date=21 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref> The tour, comprising 62 shows, was met with positivity both critically and commercially.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/one-direction-live-review-from-hammersmith-171874 |title=One Direction's Hammersmith Apollo gig | first =James | last = Robertson |date=11 January 2012 |work= The Daily Mirror |publisher= [[Trinity Mirror]] |accessdate= 8 April 2012 | archiveurl = http://www.freezepage.com/1333939607CZJAMCVUXO |archivedate=8 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.herald.ie/news/one-direction-show-has-fans-up-all-night-2999092.html |title= One Direction show has fans up all night | last =Ryan | first = Alexandra |date= 25 January 2012 |work= [[Evening Herald]] |publisher= [[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate= 8 April 2012|archiveurl= http://www.freezepage.com/1333939933IFYQZGQCXW | archivedate= 8 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last =Brandle | first = Lars|title= One Direction Live: Shriek Show in Australia | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/492534/one-direction-live-shriek-show-in-australia| work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=19 April 2012|accessdate= 9 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first1 =Cameron | last1 = Adams | last2 = Siobhan | first2 = Duck|url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/one-directions-melbourne-concert-sells-out-in-three-minutes/story-e6frf9hf-1226286954743 |title=One Direction's Melbourne concert sells out in three minutes|work=Herald Sun |location= [[Australia|AU]] |publisher= [[The Herald and Weekly Times]]|date= 2 March 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first =Bridget | last = Jones|url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/whats-on/6512032/One-Directions-NZ-tour-sold-out |title=One Direction's NZ tour sold out|work= [[Stuff.co.nz|Stuff]] | place = [[New Zealand|NZ]] | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 2 March 2012| accessdate= 1 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first = Emily | last = Hewett |url = http://www.metro.co.uk/music/877239-one-direction-tickets-fans-bombard-ticketmaster-as-ebay-touts-capitalise |title= One Direction tickets: Fans bombard Ticketmaster as eBay touts capitalise| work = [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher= [[Associated Newspapers]]| date= 1 October 2011| accessdate= 1 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title= One Direction to Headline Madison Square Garden December 3, 2012 |url = http://www.kait8.com/story/17325179/one-direction-to-headline-madison-square-garden-december-3-2012 |work= [[KAIT]] | publisher = [[Raycom Media]] |date=3 April 2012 |accessdate=8 April 2012|archiveurl= http://www.freezepage.com/1333943764HSQQZOQYGS | archivedate = 8 April 2012}}</ref> A recording of a concert from the tour, ''[[One Direction: Up All Night <U+2013> The Live Tour|Up All Night: The Live Tour]]'', was released in May 2012.<ref name="musicDVD">{{cite news | first = Lewis | last = Corner |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a376053/one-direction-perform-moments-on-tour-video.html |title = One Direction perform 'Moments' on tour | type = video | work= [[Digital Spy]] | publisher= Hearst | place = UK |date = 12 April 2012 |accessdate= 27 April 2012}}</ref> In addition to the DVD topping the charts in twenty-five countries, its global sales had exceeded 1 million copies by August 2012.<ref name="12millionsales"/><ref name =DVDWW>{{cite news | first =Rhian | last = Jones |url= http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/one-direction-live-dvd-hits-no1-in-25-countries/049138 | title= One Direction live DVD hits No.1 in 25 countries | work= [[Music Week]] | publisher = Intent Media | date = 8 June 2012 |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref> One Direction's first book to be licensed in America, ''Dare to Dream: Life as One Direction'', published in the United States in May 2012, topped [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-06-10/paperback-books/list.html |work=The New York Times | title=Best Sellers | date=10 June 2012 | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | first=Gregory | last=Cowles}}</ref>  In June 2012, Nick Gatfield, the chairman and chief executive officer of [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music Entertainment UK]], stated how he expects One Direction to represent a $100 million business empire over 2013.<ref name = "business empire">{{cite news| first =Jocelyn | last = Vena | url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1687496/one-direction-hundred-million-dollar-business.jhtml |title = One Direction Set To Become Booming $100 Million Business|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[MTV Networks]]|date=15 June 2012 |accessdate= 15 June 2012}}</ref> Gatfield was quoted as saying, "What you might not know about One Direction is that they already represent a $50 million business and that's a figure we expect to double next year".<ref name="business empire"/> In August 2012, the group's record sales exceeded 8 million singles, 3 million albums, and 1 million DVDs, and they performed "What Makes You Beautiful" at the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] in London, which represented the handover to Rio de Janeiro as the host of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref name="12millionsales"/><ref>{{cite news | first =Kia | last = Makarechi |url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/12/one-direction-closing-ceremony-olympics_n_1770803.html |title= One Direction & Closing Ceremony: Olympics Get A Dose Of 'What Makes You Beautiful' | work = [[The Huffington Post]]| date= 12 August 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> One Direction were the biggest winners of the [[2012 MTV Video Music Awards]] winning their three nominations on 6 September 2012, including [[MTV Video Music Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]].<ref name= videomusicawards>{{cite news| place = UK | first =Amelia | last = Butterfly |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/19515754 | title= One Direction win three MTV Video Music Awards in LA | work = Newsbeat | publisher = BBC|date=7 September 2012|accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref>

===2012<U+2013>13: ''Take Me Home''===
[[File:One Direction at the Logies Awards 2012.jpg|thumb|left|One Direction at red carpet of the [[Logie Awards of 2012]] in [[Melbourne]]]]
One Direction's second studio album, ''[[Take Me Home (One Direction album)|Take Me Home]]'', was released in November 2012.<ref name="TMH">{{cite web|url= https://itunes.apple.com/nl/album/take-me-home/id572141438|title= Take Me Home | work =[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |accessdate=16 November 2012|language=Dutch| location = Netherlands}}</ref> ''Take Me Home'' was written in groups and has an average of just under five songwriters per track. Savan Kotecha, Rami Yacoub, and Carl Falk, who composed One Direction's hits "What Makes You Beautiful" and "One Thing", spent six months in Stockholm developing songs for the album, and were able to shape melodies around their tones.<ref name =Wolk>{{cite news| first = Douglas | last = Wol|url= http://entertainment.time.com/2012/11/13/one-directions-songwriters-theyre-what-make-the-boy-band-beautiful/ | title = One Direction<U+2019>s songwriters: They<U+2019>re what make the boy band beautiful|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref> One Direction began recording the album in May 2012, in Stockholm at Kinglet Studios.<ref name=credits>{{cite AV media notes |title = Take Me Home |others=One Direction |date=2012 |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Syco Records]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/one-direction/354656-one-direction-sweden |title= One Direction Recording Second Album |work=MTV News |publisher=Viacom|date=11 May 2012 |accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/new-album/ |title= One Direction Enjoy "Amazing Day" In The Studio Recording New Album |publisher=Capital (Global Radio)|date=12 May 2012 |accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref> The album cover artwork features the group surrounding a traditional British K2 [[red telephone box]], a familiar sight on the streets of the UK.<ref>[http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/one-direction-reveal-album-artwork-1289666 "Squeal! One Direction reveal album artwork for Take Me Home"]. The Mirror. Retrieved 28 November 2012</ref> ''Take Me Home'' garnered mixed reviews from [[music journalism|music critics]]. There was praise for its quality of production, while it was criticised for its generic, rushed nature.<ref>{{cite news| first =Matt | last = Collar |url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/take-me-home-mw0002418914  |title = Take Me Home (CD <U+2013> Sony Music Distribution #88725475972) | publisher= [[Rovi Corporation]]| work = [[AllMusic]]| date = 11 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Al | last = Fox | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/fh8r | type = review | title = One Direction <U+2013> Take Me Home |work = [[BBC Music]] |publisher= BBC |date= 12 November 2012|accessdate= 16 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | type = review | first = Adam | last = Markovitz |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20643783,00.html | title = Take Me Home <U+2014> One Direction | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]] |date=11 November 2012 | accessdate= 16 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=NYT/><ref name=Guardian/><ref name=NZH/> The album's lead single, "[[Live While We're Young]]", released in September 2012, reached the top ten in almost every country it charted in and recorded the highest one-week opening sales figure for a song by a non-US artist in the US.<ref>{{cite news| first =Tina| last = Hart|url = http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/one-direction-have-fastest-selling-single-by-a-uk-artist/052114 | title = One Direction achieve fastest-selling single by a UK act in the US |work= Music Week |publisher= Intent Media|date= 21 October 2012 |accessdate=11 October 2012|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> The album and its second single, "[[Little Things (One Direction song)|Little Things]]", both debuted at number one in the UK simultaneously; something that One Direction became the youngest act in British chart history to achieve.<ref>{{cite news | first = Alan | last = Jones | url = http://www.musicweek.com/businessanalysis/read/official-charts-analysis-one-direction-youngest-ever-act-to-hit-no-1-in-albums-and-singles-lists/052592 |title=Official Charts Analysis: One Direction youngest ever act to score No. 1 Album and Single simultaneously |work=[[Music Week]] |publisher=Intent Media|date=19 November 2012 |accessdate=19 November 2012| location = [[United Kingdom|UK]]}}</ref> ''Take Me Home'' sold 540,000 copies in its first week in the US, debuted atop the ''Billboard'' 200, and topped the charts in more than thirty-four other countries.<ref name = "USTMHdebut">{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474059/one-directions-take-me-home-debuts-at-no-1-with-years-third-biggest-opening |title=One Direction's 'Take Me Home' Debuts at No. 1 With Year's Third-Biggest Opening | work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=20 November 2012|accessdate= 22 November 2012 | location = [[United States of America|US]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first =Tina | last = Hart|url = http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/imagem-music-signs-one-direction-hit-writer-fiona-bevan/052709 |title=Imagem Music signs One Direction hit-writer Fiona Bevan |work=[[Music Week]] |publisher=Intent Media|date=29 November 2012 | accessdate =1 December 2012|location= [[United Kingdom|UK]]}}</ref> Additionally, ''Up All Night'' and ''Take Me Home'' were the number three and number four best-selling albums of 2012 globally, each album selling over 5&nbsp;million units worldwide.<ref name="Modest Management">[http://www.modestmanagement.com/one-direction/].</ref>

One Direction performed "Little Things" at the 2012 [[Royal Variety Performance]] in the presence of [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]], and headlined a sold-out show at New York City's [[Madison Square Garden]] on 3 December 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/9690193/Royal-Variety-Performance-2012-One-Direction-and-Girls-Aloud-sing-for-The-Queen.html |title=Royal Variety Performance 2012: One Direction and Girls Aloud sing for The Queen |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]| date= 20 November 2012 | accessdate = 24 November 2012 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/473866/one-direction-headlines-sold-out-show-at-madison-square-garden |title=One Direction Headlines Sold-Out Show at Madison Square Garden|date=4 December 2012| accessdate =5 December 2012|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media| first =Andrew | last = Hampp}}</ref>

In February 2013, One Direction released a cover version of "[[One Way or Another]]" and "[[Teenage Kicks]]", "[[One Way or Another (Teenage Kicks)]]", as the 2013 [[Comic Relief]] single.<ref name="Robertson">{{cite news|url= http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/one-direction-reflect-on-life-changing-1535079 |title='We are the most selfish people ever': One Direction reflect on 'life changing' charity trip to Africa 'slums'|date=15 January 2013|accessdate=16 February 2013 | work =Metro| first =James | last = Robertson}}</ref> As part of their involvement with the UK charity, One Direction travelled to Ghana to volunteer at a children's hospital, visit a school and make donations.

In addition, the [[Official Charts Company]] revealed that One Direction had sold 2,425,000 records in the UK by February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-brit-awards-2013-the-real-winners-revealed-1869/|title= The BRIT Awards 2013: The biggest selling nominees revealed|publisher= [[Official Charts Company]]| first =Dan | last = Lane|date= 20 February 2013 | accessdate = 21 February 2013}}</ref>  One Direction embarked on their second concert tour in February 2013, the [[Take Me Home Tour (One Direction)|Take Me Home Tour]].<ref>{{cite news| first =Jocelyn | last = Vena|url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1682975/one-direction-tour-dates.jhtml | title= One Direction Announce US Dates On 2013 World Tour | work = News |publisher=MTV |date=12 April 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> The concert tour consists of over 100 shows in Europe, North America and Australasia. Ticket sales reached 300,000 within a day of release in the UK and Ireland, which included a six-date sell-out at London's [[The O2 Arena]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/one-direction/349694-one-direction-tickets |title=One Direction Fans in Ticket-Buying Frenzy |work=[[MTV News|News]] | publisher =[[MTV Networks|MTV]] |date=26 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> In the Australian and New Zealand markets, tickets grossed US$15.7 million, with all 190,000 tickets being sold for the eighteen shows to be held.<ref>{{cite news| first =Brittany | last = Stack |url= http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/how-one-direction-cashed-in-on-their-hugely-successful-australian-tour/story-e6freuy9-1226341685202 |title=How One Direction cashed in on their hugely successful Australian tour |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]] | place = [[Australia|AU]]|publisher =[[News Limited]]|date= 29 April 2012 |accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref> The tour received critical acclaim from music critics who praised the band's live vocals and their performance abilities and was a commercial success, selling 1,635,000 tickets from 134 shows.<ref name="Box Office">[http://onedirectionmusic.com/].</ref>

===2013<U+2013>present: ''Midnight Memories'' and ''This Is Us''===
[[File:One Direction 2, 2013.jpg|thumb|right|One Direction on their [[Take Me Home Tour (One Direction)|Take Me Home Tour]] in 2013]]
''[[One Direction: This Is Us]]'', a 3D documentary and concert movie about the group directed by [[Morgan Spurlock]] and produced by Spurlock, Ben Winston, Adam Milano and Simon Cowell, was released by [[TriStar Pictures]] on 30 August 2013.<ref name="3Dfilm">{{cite news | url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474195/one-direction-3d-film-gets-super-director|title= One Direction 3D Film Gets 'Super' Director| first = Marc | last = Schneider|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date= 13 November 2012|accessdate=15 November 2012|location= [[New York City|New York]]}}</ref> The film features the song "[[Best Song Ever (song)|Best Song Ever]]", released on 22 July 2013. "Best Song Ever" slated to serve as the lead single of the group's third studio album ''[[Midnight Memories]]''.<ref>{{citation|last=Brandie|first=Lars|date=26 June 2013|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1568160/one-direction-tease-best-song-ever-release-new-movie-trailer|title=One Direction Tease 'Best Song Ever'; Release New Movie Trailer | newspaper = [[Billboard.com|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= One Direction Announce New Single 'Best Song Ever'| place = UK | url= http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/one-direction/384889-one-direction-new-single-best-song-ever-this-is-us-new-trailer |publisher= MTV| accessdate= 1 July 2013}}</ref> The film was a box office success, topping the UK and US box offices and grossing over $60 million worldwide. It is currently the fourth highest grossing concert movie.<ref name="Box Office">[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=musicconcert.htm].</ref>

On 16 May 2013, the band announced their first stadium tour, the Where We Are Tour, which is set to commence in April 2014. They plan to donate <U+00A3>200,000 of the tour's ticket sales to the [[Stand Up to Cancer]] charity.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ledger|first=Emma|title= One Direction add More dates to the Where We Are Tour 2014! |url= http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/one-direction-tickets-tour-2014-1910365 |publisher=The Daily Mirror| place = UK | accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref>

On 30 May 2013, the band announced a partnership with [[Office Depot]] on a limited-edition capsule collection of back to school supplies. They also confirmed that a portion of the proceeds from the alliance would go toward an anti-bullying educational program intended to promote kinder behavior in schools. The campaign has raised over one million dollars.

On 23 November and in support of ''Midnight Memories'', the band participated in "1D Day",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1dday.com/ |title=Welcome to 1D Day <U+2013> 1D Day <U+2013> One Direction |publisher=1dday.com |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a533434/one-direction-1d-day-live-stream-watch.html |title=One Direction '1D Day' Live Stream - watch - Showbiz News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=23 November 2013 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> a day dedicated to One Direction fans. The day constituted of a landmark 7.5 hour socially interactive [[YouTube]] live-stream featuring live band performances, celebrity guests including, [[Simon Cowell]], [[Cindy Crawford]], [[Piers Morgan]], [[Jerry Springer]] and many more. The event was unique not only due to its long runtime but the unprecedented use of social media whereby fans got to participate in the show interact directly with the band via [[Google+ Hangout]].

''Midnight Memories'' was released globally on 25 November 2013. The album was described by the band as edgier and as having a "slightly rockier tone" than their previous efforts.<ref>{{cite web|last= Percival| first= Ashley|title= One Direction Big Announcement: 'Where We Are' Stadium Tour Confirmed For 2014|url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/05/16/one-direction-big-announcement-where-we-are-tour-2014_n_3284795.html |publisher= The Huffington Post|accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> "[[Story of My Life (One Direction song)|Story of My Life]]" was revealed as the second single of the album with each member posting a photo from their childhood. Afterwards, the cover of the single was posted on the One Direction account.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2454573/One-Direction-share-adorable-childhood-photos-promote-new-single-Story-My-Life.html|title=Breaking hearts from the get go: One Direction share adorable childhood photos to promote new single Story of My Life|work=Daily Mail|date=11 October 2013|first=Joanna|last=Crawley|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebuzz.com/2013-10-10/one-direction-announces-story-of-my-life-single-through-baby-photos/|title=One Direction Announces 'Story of My Life' Single Through Baby Photos|work=Celebuzz|date=11 October 2013|last=Chung|first=Gabrielle}}</ref> On 11 October 2013, One Direction revealed the cover and track listing for the album with the track listing being revealed through a "#MidnightMemoriesTrackQuiz" on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mstarz.com/articles/20167/20131011/one-direction-midnight-memories-cover-art-tracklist-revealed-photo-zayn.htm|title=One Direction 'Midnight Memories' Cover Art, Tracklist Revealed [PHOTO]: Zayn, Harry, Niall, Louis and Liam Announce Twitter 'Track Quiz' Contest for Fans|work=Mstarz|date=11 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5755387/one-direction-unveils-midnight-memories-artwork-track-list|title=One Direction Unveils 'Midnight Memories' Artwork, Track List|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=11 October 2013}}</ref> It was confirmed that the band would perform on both the [[The X Factor (U.S. TV series)|American]] and [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|British]] versions of ''The X Factor'' in order to promote their  album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heatworld.com/Celeb-News/2013/10/One-Direction-confirmed-for-The-X-Factor/|title=One Direction confirmed for The X Factor 2013 live shows|work=heatworld.com|last=Lewis|first=Anna}}</ref>

The album debuted at number one in the UK and in the US, making them the first group to debut at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with its first three albums, and the second to reach the top after [[The Monkees]] in 1967.<ref name="Billboard record">{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=One Direction Scores Historic Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5812384/one-direction-scores-historic-third-no-1-album-on-billboard-200-chart|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=4 December 2013|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>

In December 2013, One Direction broke yet another UK sales record with the [[DVD]] and [[Blu-Ray]] release of their [[concert film|3-D concert film]] "[[One Direction: This Is Us|This is Us]]". In point of fact, nearly 270,000 copies of the movie were sold in the UK within three days of its release, beating the record previously set by ''[[Michael Jackson: This Is It|Michael Jackson<U+2019>s This Is It]]'' in 2010 by 10,000 copies.<ref name="Official Charts">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-beat-michael-jacksons-chart-record-2695/#.Ur4VQbWDpK0.twitter |title=One Direction beat Michael Jackson<U+2019>s chart record |publisher=Officialcharts.com |date=23 December 2013 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> The group was named Top Global artists of 2013 by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI]] due to strong digital downloads, physical albums, on-demand streams, and music videos.<ref name="IFPI">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/one-direction-named-top-global-recording-artist-in-new-award-9093917.html|title=One Direction named top Global Recording Artist in new award|publisher=The Independent|date= 30 January 2014|accessdate=30 January 2014|location=London|first=Adam|last=Sherwin}}</ref>

