| pos = right
}}
One Direction's debut studio album, ''Up All Night'' (2011), is predominantly a pop music record, containing elements of [[teen pop]], [[dance-pop]], [[pop rock]], with [[Synthpop|electropop]] and [[rock music|rock]] influences.<ref name="Rosen">{{cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/up-all-night-20120328 | title = One Direction <U+2013> Up All Night | work= Rolling Stone | publisher= [[Jann Wenner]] | author-link = Jody Rosen | first = Jody | last = Rosen |date= 28 March 2012 |accessdate= 16 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="allmusic3">{{cite web | first = Jon | last = O'Brien|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/one-direction-mn0002766592|title=One Direction| work = All Music |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="Chisling">{{cite news| first = Matthew | last = Chisling |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-all-night-r2324993/review |title= Up All Night&nbsp;<U+2013> One Direction|publisher=AllMusic |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref><ref name="Lipshutz">{{cite news| first =Jason | last = Lipshutz |url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/502856/one-direction-up-all-night-track-by-track-review |title= One Direction, 'Up All Night': Track-By-Track Review |location=New York |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> [[Digital Spy]]'s Robert Copsey described the album as a "collection of PG pop rock with killer choruses",<ref>{{cite web| first =Robert | last = Copsey|url= http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/albumreviews/a352333/one-direction-up-all-night-album-review.html |title=One Direction: 'Up All Night' | type = album review |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=Hearst | place = UK|date=22 November 2011 |accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref> while ''[[The New York Times]]'' considered it "full of easy rock-inflected pop, blithe and sometimes clever."<ref name=autogenerated11>{{cite news | first = Jon | last = Caramanica| url= http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/28/arts/music/one-direction-the-boy-band-plays-the-beacon-theater.html | work= The New York Times | title= One Direction, the Boy Band, Plays the Beacon Theater | date=27 May 2012|accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> Jason Lipshutz of ''Billboard'' acknowledged that the album demonstrates an originality in sound that was "necessary for the revitalization of the boy band movement".<ref name = "Lipshutz" />  The songs "One Thing" and "What Makes You Beautiful" were particularly noted for the genres of power pop and pop rock, for their "powerhouse" [[guitar riff]]s and "forceful" choruses.<ref name="DS1" /><ref name="cowbell">{{cite web | first = Zachary | last = Houle | url = http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/155316-one-direction-up-all-night/ | title= One Direction: Up All Night| work= [[PopMatters]] | publisher= [[Buzz Media]] | date= 16 March 2012 | accessdate = 31 March 2012}}</ref><ref name="Rosen" /><ref>{{cite web| first =Lewis | last = Corner |url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a363531/one-direction-one-thing-single-review.html | title= One Direction: 'One Thing' <U+2013> Single review |work=[[Digital Spy]] | publisher= Hearst | place = UK|date= 2 February 2012 |accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref>

Their second studio album, ''Take Me Home'' (2012), is characterised by rock-inherited pop, prominent [[electric guitar]] riffs, bright [[synthesisers]], a [[Homogeneity and heterogeneity|homogeneous]] sound and message, and the pitch-correcting software [[Auto-Tune]].<ref name= NYT>{{cite news| first = Jon | last = Caramanica | url= http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/arts/music/one-direction-rides-boy-band-wave-with-take-me-home.html |work = The New York Times | title=Riding the Boy Band Wave While It Lasts | date=14 November 2012|accessdate= 30 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/nov/08/one-direction-take-me-review | title = One Direction: Take Me Home | type = review | work = The Guardian | author-link = Alexis Petridis | first = Alexis | last = Petridis | date=8 November 2012|accessdate=9 November 2012 | location=London}}</ref><ref name = NZH>{{cite news|url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10847430 | type = album review | title = One Direction <U+2014> Take Me Home|publisher= [[APN News & Media]]|date= 15 November 2012|accessdate = 16 November 2012 | work = [[The New Zealand Herald]]| first = Lyndia | last = Jenkin}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| first = Douglas | last = Wol|url= http://entertainment.time.com/2012/11/13/one-directions-songwriters-theyre-what-make-the-boy-band-beautiful/ |title=One Direction<U+2019>s songwriters: They<U+2019>re what make the boy band beautiful|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= 28 June 2012 |accessdate= 25 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first = Matt | last = Collar |url = http://www.allmusic.com/album/take-me-home-mw0002418914 | title = Take Me Home (CD <U+2013> Sony Music Distribution #88725475972) | publisher=Rovi Corporation|work=AllMusic|date=11 November 2012 |accessdate= 16 November 2012}}</ref> [[Alexis Petridis]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' interpreted its signature sound as a "peppy, [[synth]]-bolstered take on early-80s [[New Wave music|new-wave]] pop, heavy on clipped rhythms and chugging guitars," which, he said, is at least an improvement on the substitute contemporary [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] "that was once the grim lot of the boyband."<ref name = Guardian /> Jon Caramanica, writing in ''The New York Times'', considered the album "far more mechanical" than their debut album, although noted that it is sonically and lyrically similar.<ref name=NYT /> The album's lyricism speaks of falling in love, [[unrequited love]], the insistence that flaws are what make a person unique, commitment, jealousy and longing for past significant others.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Guardian/><ref name= NZH /><ref name = "autogenerated12">{{cite news | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/12/one-direction-lyrics-take-me-home_n_2118855.html |title=One Direction lyrics: 'Take Me Home' pushes boundaries, targets older audience| date= 15 November 2012| accessdate= 16 March 2013 | work = [[The Huffington Post]] | first=Madeline | last=Boardman}}</ref>

Erica Futterman for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' favoured their live [[Musical acoustics|acoustic]] performances as both showing, "Horan's ability to play guitar, as well as One Direction's admirable live vocals. There was no need to worry about a backing track or a bum note, a pleasant realization at a pop show."<ref>{{cite news| first =Erica | last = Futterman |url= http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/one-direction-make-a-play-for-longevity-on-first-american-headlining-tour-20120527 |title= One Direction Make a Play For Longevity on First American Headlining Tour |work = Rolling Stone|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]] |date=27 May 2012 |accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[Herald Sun]]''{{'}}s Cameron Adams opined that One Direction have "strong pop voices".<ref>{{cite news| first =Cameron | last = Adams |url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/one-direction-infection-sweeps-melbourne/story-e6frf96f-1226329537630 |title = One Direction infection sweeps Melbourne |work=Herald Sun |location= [[Australia|AU]] |publisher= [[The Herald and Weekly Times]] |date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref> Melody Lau of the ''[[National Post]]'' wrote, "It's easy to get lost in inherent appeal of their perfectly coiffed dos and almost-too-put-together preppy style but somewhere in the midst of all the love-struck squeals of teenage girls are guys who can actually sing and, to a certain extent, entertain."<ref>{{cite news| first = Melody | last = Lau |url= http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/06/01/concert-review-one-direction-are-mostly-killer-with-some-filler/ |title= Concert Review: One Direction are mostly killer with some filler |work= National Post |location= [[Canada|CA]] |publisher= [[Postmedia Network]] | date= 1 June 2012 | accessdate = 11 June 2012}}</ref> Jane Stevenson of the portal site [[Canoe.ca|Canoe]] concurred: "What I didn't really prepare myself for was that they all can actually sing in concert."<ref>{{cite news| first = Jane | last = Stevenson |url = http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/O/One_Direction/ConcertReviews/2012/05/30/19815201-qmi.html |title= Concert Review: Live Review: One Direction in TO |work= [[Canoe.ca|Jam! Canoe]] |publisher=[[Qu<U+00E9>becor M<U+00E9>dia]] |date=30 May 2012 | accessdate = 11 June 2012}}</ref> Chris Richards, writing in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', dissented from the approval: "As the five traded couplets, it was tough to imagine a future [[Justin Timberlake]], [[Ricky Martin]] or [[Bobby Brown]] emerging from the pack. No one voice stood out."<ref>{{cite news| first =Chris | last = Richards| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/one-direction-show-polite-boy-band-excites-squealing-fans/2012/05/25/gJQAmYxVpU_story.html |work=The Washington Post | title = One Direction whips Patriot Center into a G-rated frenzy | date = 25 May 2012|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> Mike Wass of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] felt One Direction's "surprisingly accomplished effort" of [[Kings of Leon]]'s "[[Use Somebody]]" proved that One Direction are "more than capable" of evolving their sound.<ref>{{cite news| first =Mike | last = Wass |url= http://idolator.com/6351471/one-direction-live-in-sydney-concert-review |title=One Direction Live In Sydney: Concert Review |work= [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |publisher=[[Buzz Media]]|date=13 April 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>

Their third album ''Midnight Memories'' (2013) is a pop rock record, a slight departure from the band's original teen pop sound. Liam Payne called Midnight Memories a "slightly rockier and edgier" album than their previous material. The album is heavily influenced by 80s rock<ref name=Rebellion>[http://whstherebellion.com/?p=51482].</ref> and folk music and briefly integrates elements of dubstep, notably in "Little White Lies". The album's lyrical themes primarily revolve around love, heartbreak and sexual intercourse. Many critics praised its lyrical depth and musical composition<ref name="Hollywood Reporter">{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/one-directions-midnight-memories-what-660135 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Kyle | last=Jaeger | title=One Direction's 'Midnight Memories': What the Critics Are Saying | date=26 November 2013}}</ref>

==Philanthropy==

In 2011, the band performed on the [[Children in Need 2011]] broadcast, helping raise over 26 million pounds.<ref name="Daily Mail">{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2063412/Children-In-Need-2011-Sir-Terry-Wogan-wowed-Tess-Daly-Alesha-Dixon-Fearne-Cotton.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Wogan's angels: Sir Terry is wowed by golden girls trio Tess Daly, Alesha Dixon and Fearne Cotton on Children in Need | first1=Jessica | last1=Satherley | first2=J J | last2=Anisiobi | date=18 November 2011}}</ref>

In 2012 they extended their involvement with Children in Need as they opened the telecast with a performance of their single [[Live While We're Young]]. The group said it was "incredible" to be involved in the charity event as it was something that they had "always watched as children".<ref name="BBC">{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-20367022 | work=BBC News | title=One Direction: 'Incredible to open Children In Need' | date=16 November 2012}}</ref>

In February 2013, One Direction released a medley of "[[One Way or Another]]" and "[[Teenage Kicks]]", "[[One Way or Another (Teenage Kicks)]]", as the 2013 [[Comic Relief]] single.<ref name="Robertson"/>

For [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]<U+2019>s Christmas campaign, they will be filming a set of pleas to their fans and the general public, asking them to donate <U+00A3>2.<ref name="Sugarscape">[http://www.sugarscape.com/main-topics/film-and-tv/999397/one-direction-join-itv%E2%80%99s-text-santa-charity-campaign].</ref>

In September 2012, Niall Horan organised an event to raise money for Irish Autism Action and another charity called and Temporary Emergency Accommodation Mullingar based in his hometown. Due to overwhelming demand to participate in the fundraising, the ticket website for the event broke down. Horan's brother Greg commented on the website crash, saying that "there were 500 tickets and they were all snapped up pretty quick".<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.sugarscape.com/main-topics/homepage/764642/niall-horans-charity-event-crashes-website].</ref> Horan later reflected on the fundraisings saying that he was "honoured to be able to give back to his community".

In 2013, band members Liam Payne and Harry Styles partnered with Trekstock, a leading cancer charity in order to help raise money for cancer research.<ref name="Trekstock">
[http://trekstock.com/our-story/patrons-ambassadors/].</ref>  As ambassadors of the charity, the duo collaborated to offer the chance for one fan and a friend to win an evening out with them in return for a donation to the charity as part of an exclusive "#HangwithLiam&Harry" global campaign. They had originally set a goal of raising $500,000 and ended up raising $784,984. Trekstock later added that this amount would allow them to "complete funding of their Hodgkin's lymphoma trial, in the hope of offering a much brighter future to thousands of children and young people affected by this form of disease. One Direction were named the most charitable in 2013 behind [[Taylor Swift]] by social change organization [[DoSomething.org]].<ref name="Do Something">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5847924/taylor-swift-one-direction-top-list-of-most-charitable-stars |title=Taylor Swift, One Direction Top List of Most Charitable Stars |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref>

==Image==
[[File:OneDirectionStockholm.JPG|thumb|left|200px|One Direction greet Swedish fans in [[Stockholm]], May 2012]]
Neil McCormick of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', in an article on One Direction's success in North America, notes that Americans had left a gap in the market and it took the prominence of [[Justin Bieber]] to demonstrate that there still was a market for "clean cut, wholesome, whiter-than-white, middle class parent friendly pop: cute boys advocating puppy love.  And what could be better than one cute boy, if not five?"<ref>{{cite news | first = Neil | last = McCormick |url= http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopmusic/9111003/The-Wanted-and-One-Direction-why-British-boybands-are-conquering-America.html |title=The Wanted & One Direction: why British boybands are conquering America |work= The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date= 28 February 2012|accessdate= 17 March 2012}}</ref> One Direction have been described as sparking a resurgence in the interest in boy bands, and as forming part of a new "[[British Invasion]]" in the United States.<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite news| first =Kerry | last = O'Shea |url = http://www.irishcentral.com/ent/One-Direction-BritishIrish-boy-band--about-to-explode-in-America-says-Simon-Cowell--142303325.html |title=One Direction, British/Irish boy band about to explode in America says Simon Cowell |work =[[IrishCentral]] | date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite news| first = Lyndsey | last = Parker |url= http://ca.music.yahoo.com/blogs/reality-rocks/british-coming-one-direction-set-conquer-america-202911123.html |title=The British Are Coming! One Direction Set To Conquer America |work=[[Yahoo! News|News]] | publisher =Yahoo! |date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite news| first = Jocelyn | last = Vena|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1681029/the-wanted-one-direction-boy-bands.jhtml |title= The Wanted Vs. One Direction: A Boy Band Cheat Sheet |work=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[MTV Networks]] |date=14 March 2012 | accessdate =31 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news| first =Brian | last = Mansfield |url = http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/ontheverge/story/2012-03-07/one-direction/53425236/1 |title=Meet UK boy band One Direction |work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company|Gannett Co]] |date=9 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated9>{{cite news| url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2113904/British-boy-band-One-Direction-cause-fan-frenzy-make-U-S-television-debut-performance-Today-show.html | title= British boy band One Direction cause fan frenzy as they make US television debut performance on Today show |work= The Daily Mail | publisher = [[Associated Newspapers]]|date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012 |location= London}}</ref><ref name= Greene>{{cite web | first = Andy | last = Greene | url = http://rollingstoneindia.com/features/the-new-british-invasion-boy-bands/ | title = The New British Invasion: Boy Bands |work= Rolling Stone| publisher = [[Jann Wenner]] |date= 8 May 2012 | accessdate = 11 June 2012}}</ref> Bill Werde, a representative of [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] magazine, commented, "There's a lot of possibility here, there's a lot of upside, that level of talent with those kinds of looks, it's really a perfect storm for a massive, massive successful phenomenon."<ref name="guardian1">{{cite news| first = Caspar Llewellyn | last = Smith |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/mar/15/one-direction-fab-five-america |title = One Direction: the fab five take America |work=The Guardian| location=London |date=15 March 2012| accessdate= 31 March 2012}}</ref>

Sonny Takhar, the chief executive officer of Syco Records, attributes the breakthrough to the power of [[social media]]. "Sometimes you feel the song's the star, but it's not like that here&nbsp;<U+2013> it's the act," he said. "It's a real moment. Social media has become the new radio, it's never broken an act globally like this before."<ref name="guardian1"/> Will Bloomfield, the group's manager, added, "These guys live online, and so do their fans."<ref name= Greene /> Their management employs a social media team and the members all tweet themselves, "which helps create the illusion that they couldn't be any closer to their fans," according to Caspar Llewellyn Smith, writing for ''The Guardian''.<ref name = "guardian1" /> One Direction's Twitter account had amassed 10 million followers by February 2013, with the account gaining followers at an average of 21,000 per day.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://twittercounter.com/compare/one%20direction/week/followers | title = One Direction Twitter Stats |work= Counter| publisher= Twitter | accessdate= 15 March 2013}}</ref> Each member is known for his feature;<ref name=Abrams>{{cite news| first =Stephanie | last = Abrahams |url = http://entertainment.time.com/2012/04/06/behind-the-hype-can-one-direction-save-the-boy-band/ | title = Can One Direction Save the Boy Band? | work = Time | date = 6 April 2012 | accessdate= 27 April 2012}}</ref> Horan is "the cute one",<ref name = Abrams/> Malik is "the quiet and mysterious one",<ref name="  Abrams" /> Payne is "the sensible one",<ref name = Abrams /> Styles is "the charming one"<ref name = Abrams /> and Tomlinson is "the funny one".<ref name=Abrams/> Horan commented on One Direction as a boy band, "People think that a boy band is air-grabs and [being] dressed in all one colour.  We're boys in a band.  We're trying to do something different from what people would think is the typical kind of boy band.  We're trying to do different kinds of music and we're just trying to be ourselves, not squeaky clean."<ref name = "nationalpost1">{{cite news| first = Leah | last = Collins | url= http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/12/one-direction-is-more-than-just-another-boy-band/ |title = One Direction: X Factor boy band on what sets them apart | work = National Post | location= [[Canada|CA]] |publisher = [[Postmedia Network]] | date= 12 March 2012 | accessdate= 17 March 2012}}</ref> Leah Collins, writing for the ''[[National Post]]'', remarked that One Direction had succeeded on the latter front,<ref name = "nationalpost1" /> "For the most part, that just means the group presents themselves as typical, goofy and uncensored teenage boys&nbsp;<U+2013> posting jokey YouTube videos, for instance, or boozing at awards shows."<ref name="nationalpost1" /> Writing for ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Kitty Empire]] opined, "One Direction fulfil a great many boy band prerequisites (looks, soppy lyrics, tune-grasp, fame-lust) but their lack of routines points to the subtle digressions afoot here".<ref>{{cite news| author-link = Kitty Empire | first = Kitty | last = Empire |url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/jan/08/one-direction-x-factor-live |title= One Direction | type = review |date=7 January 2012 |work= The Observer |publisher= [[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate= 8 April 2012 | archiveurl = http://www.freezepage.com/1333939139CSPGVONNPC |archivedate= 8 April 2012 |location= London}}</ref>

